00:01.140 --> 00:10.580
Okay, the tape is going. First, all I wanted to know was how you first got
involved with the fantasy field. Did you read it as a girl, an adolescent, and

00:10.580 --> 00:21.200
grow up with it? How did you get involved with it? Well, not really. I started
reading it in my early 20s. I had read science fiction when I was younger. But I

00:21.200 --> 00:32.680
discovered fantasy when I was about 23 or 24. And I connected with it more
strongly than I had with science fiction. and I've been interested in fantasy

00:32.680 --> 00:45.460
almost exclusively since as far as as far as genre fiction is concerned I don't
read any science fiction anymore okay in other words you didn't you just didn't

00:45.460 --> 00:56.740
grow up reading reading the pulps the magazines then I never I never liked the
pulps particularly I liked fairy tales when I was quite little but somehow I

00:56.740 --> 01:07.340
never thought of them as being suitable for me as a teenage reader or as an
adult reader. It took me a long time to connect and see that fantasy was really

01:07.340 --> 01:18.160
suited for adults, as well. I think a lot of people feel that way about fantasy.
They start reading science fiction perhaps partly because it seems more adult

01:18.160 --> 01:31.500
than fantasy. I don't think that's at all true. Fantasy has a stronger symbolic
meaning for it. Science fiction, in a lot of ways, is a lot more simplistic in

01:31.500 --> 01:43.060
its worldviews. It's a feeling around for symbols that don't have an ancient
heritage, or an ancient long existence in our subconscious and our culture.

01:46.280 --> 01:57.300
Okay, what about the writing part of it? How did you get involved in that? Well,
I started writing science fiction as well, like when I was about 13. Got my

01:57.300 --> 02:06.400
first little rejection letter, a pleasant little letter from John Campbell,
telling me I misspelled one of the words in my title with a one-word title. I

02:06.400 --> 02:15.040
was so embarrassed that I never submitted him anything else. That, again, it was
many years before I ceased to write science fiction stories, started writing

02:15.040 --> 02:23.760
fantasy instead. Although I'd also written horror stories simultaneously. and
some of those actually have turned out to be publishable, ones that I wrote when

02:23.760 --> 02:35.700
I was a teenager. The science fiction all garbage that I wrote when I was a
teenager. My major writing is I think it's all been fantasy. Yeah, I have to

02:35.700 --> 02:44.040
confess that I haven't been able to find much background on your, you know,
except for the works you published on much else. Have you published any science

02:44.040 --> 02:57.220
fiction at all? No. Everything I've published has been fantasy, and with a good
deal of horror stories thrown in which could be considered dark fantasy. Now you

02:57.220 --> 03:09.820
have some involvement with a fanzine, don't you? No, I don't. I used to publish
a fanzine about feminist fantasy and science fiction, but I haven't done that

03:09.820 --> 03:20.520
for a long time. There's been no time for things like that. And I did a little
newsletter about women warriors to this kind of an interest of mine. But I

03:20.520 --> 03:29.900
haven't had time to do that lately either because I have to make a living from
my writing. Okay, what was that reference I saw? I think it was in Amazon's,

03:30.040 --> 03:40.540
too, to fantasy and terror. Oh, that was something I... That's probably how I
entered the professional field, although that wasn't a professional magazine. I

03:40.540 --> 03:52.240
think it was a nice magazine. I started publishing it not really knowing what
fandom was. I was involved with literary magazines and, you know, university

03:52.240 --> 04:03.080
little magazines, and I thought it would be real interesting to do something
like that. That was all fantasy stories and horror stories. So I got to, I found

04:03.080 --> 04:10.600
some people that wrote those sorts of things, and I started doing this magazine.
And, like, after I got one issue out, I started getting magazines just like it

04:10.600 --> 04:19.220
from 100 other editors. I was really surprised to find out it wasn't her
original idea at all, that they were usually called Fancy. I did that until

04:19.220 --> 04:24.220
about 1975. From 1972 to 1975, I did seven issues.

04:28.540 --> 04:38.780
Before I quit doing it, I think it had developed into a rather pleasant magazine
as professional as you could be without having any real distribution or backing.

04:40.020 --> 04:52.560
but I just got tired of doing it it stopped okay what about another one I saw a
reference to I'm not sure what this is Windhaven that was the feminist fantasy

04:52.560 --> 05:04.300
and science fiction magazine that I started doing after I got tired of doing
fantasy and terror I guess I was just really interested in small press projects

05:04.300 --> 05:17.820
I'm not quite sure why I still write for some small presses I like the energy
that small press publishers have, but of course you can't break even on it. You

05:17.820 --> 05:27.780
can't make money on it. It usually costs more money. You can only do it for as
long as you feel this personal involvement, and after a while you just get

05:27.780 --> 05:37.660
overwhelmed and tired and you stop doing it. But that did give me some
background for when I contracted my first professional anthology, the publisher

05:37.660 --> 05:46.740
was already aware of who I was and what I was capable of doing which was a
surprise to me because I'd never sent him copies of my magazine he knew all

05:46.740 --> 05:58.100
about them and thought they were good magazines so they gave me a professional
contract my first break into actually making a living as a writer and editor and

05:58.100 --> 06:08.440
that's what you're doing now you can make your living at it yep one of the small
percentage doesn't have to do anything else Okay, that must be great. Listen,

06:08.540 --> 06:16.400
let me go on for just a little bit. Well, right before I get to some of your
work, reading the little headpieces you had in Amazons 2 to some of those

06:16.400 --> 06:27.980
stories, there was one that intrigued me. You said that many modern authors are
weak and lazy in their research for heroic fantasy. I got the impression you

06:27.980 --> 06:37.380
were implying that a heroic fantasy should be somehow based upon a, I don't
know, familiar environment, say an ancient Anglo-Saxon, medieval kind of

06:37.380 --> 06:45.480
background. Is that what you meant? No, that's really not what I meant at all. I
think most heroic fantasy is based on something really familiar, and really

06:45.480 --> 06:56.280
Anglo-Saxon and European, but they don't even, the writers of this sort of
fiction don't even research that. They just take a very superficial gleaning

06:56.280 --> 07:06.500
from what we all have in our consciousness about what it must have been like,
and they try to invent from there. And what they end up inventing is something

07:06.500 --> 07:19.800
that is tremendously superficial, almost comic book-like, rather than literary.
Whereas, if they were to do a lot of reading in historical writing, they would

07:19.800 --> 07:33.120
find out that the ancient world is a lot more complex and a lot more interesting
than their very facile fantasies about some Anglo-Europe that they never

07:33.120 --> 07:50.080
researched. I kind of would like to see more fantasy stories that weren't Anglo
at all. And much of my major work is that in a vaguely Asian world, but it

07:50.080 --> 07:58.780
wouldn't even have to be that. Something that was truly complex and different
from our own world would be very interesting. But usually, no matter how people

07:58.780 --> 08:09.760
try, they come up with things that sound Anglo-Europe. And I think it's their
essential laziness. They write fantasies because they think they can make

08:09.760 --> 08:20.400
everything up without having to read anything else first. So they end up writing
silly things. You wouldn't be saying, though, that it wouldn't be possible to

08:20.400 --> 08:33.240
write heroic fantasy which has no kind of roots whatsoever? I think it would be
very possible. I can't think of an example where it's been done. Okay. I think

08:33.240 --> 08:44.040
I'm saying this right now. Tomoe goes in? That's right. Okay. I have to confess
I know nothing about Japanese history or legend, but I assume that it is based

08:44.040 --> 08:58.500
on actual history and legend. Would that be correct? That's pretty correct. The
world that Tomoe lives in is called Naipone. and it's very strongly based on

08:58.500 --> 09:10.620
Japanese myth and Japanese history, but if anybody reads it thinking they'll
learn a lot about Japanese myth and history, they'll be wrong because naipone is

09:10.620 --> 09:24.720
its own world, and a lot of that stuff is not very loosely based. Some of it is
very rigidly based to the heavy mixture of invention and actual belief. Well,

09:24.840 --> 09:31.120
for instance, when I finished the two books that you've written so far, I was
kind of proud of myself, and then I said, gosh, I know something about Japanese

09:31.120 --> 09:39.180
legend and history now. I said, if that's what samurais are like, I like them.
For instance, would my impression of the samurais be wrong? Is that pretty close

09:39.180 --> 09:55.700
to what they were? Well, I think there is the general feel of the world created
in those two books is as near as I can figure out as an amateur historian reads

09:55.700 --> 10:04.960
about it incessantly, that that is pretty much what their behavior patterns
were, their thinking patterns, and their society. In general, the samurai were

10:04.960 --> 10:18.240
like that, sure. But what I was thinking in terms... I have come in across some
people who believe that they now know all about Japanese mythology because of

10:18.240 --> 10:28.420
the way it was portrayed in that book. But I changed some things to suit the
world that I was creating, and anybody that wants to know about Japanese history

10:28.420 --> 10:38.360
really should read history books. And people that want to be entertained by
fantasy based on that should read my books and a few other books like that.

10:39.920 --> 10:48.600
Okay, what about some of those monsters like the Tengu or the Bakenmonos or
whatever they would call them? Is there any basis for those? The Tengu and the

10:48.600 --> 11:01.900
Bacamono, and also the Kappa vampire, those are all real. They're taken from
mythology, some of the most off-the-wall aspects of them. Just a second, there's

11:01.900 --> 11:04.980
somebody at the door. Okay. Go away. There's no trouble.

11:20.280 --> 11:28.780
okay I sent them away okay if you're sure it's okay again if you weren't
expecting me I feel kind of bad about this that interrupting you I told them to

11:28.780 --> 11:39.440
drop by in half an hour okay okay anyway I forget what I was saying you were
just finishing up the answer about the Bakamonos and the Tengu they were based

11:39.440 --> 11:49.960
they were definitely based I was thinking of the Kappa which people find
difficult to believe I wasn't putting them on, like a blood-sucking animal that

11:49.960 --> 12:01.120
can be placated with pickles and cucumbers. They think that's a joke, but that's
something that the Japanese really used to believe. I suppose in some outlying

12:01.120 --> 12:13.760
areas they still believe it. Those particular types of creatures are real. There
are some other creatures in that series that aren't real. Okay, did you have any

12:13.760 --> 12:26.000
particular impetus or inspiration behind those volumes? Behind which? Those
volumes, the two in the Tomoe Gozan series. It's hard to say. I suppose part of

12:26.000 --> 12:34.900
it was just my feeling that most of the heroic fantasy written had been pretty
similar, no matter how varied the authors tried to be. They were writing the

12:34.900 --> 12:49.780
same things, which were superficially Anglo-European, either Viking or Camelot
or something like that. Really predictable. Conan. So I wanted to do something

12:49.780 --> 13:03.800
different. I'm not quite sure why. I chose it to be something based loosely on
Japanese ancient history and myth. My stepmother is from Thailand, so I've

13:03.800 --> 13:15.840
always had Asian friends and relatives, but they weren't Japanese. The only
thing I could figure out was my major and participants for really liking the

13:15.840 --> 13:29.180
Japanese legends and history would be cinema. I mean, I've really been very fond
of samurai films, essentially. I started starting out like most people with

13:29.180 --> 13:43.060
Seven Samurai and other films by Akita Kurosawa. And then being lucky to live in
an area that has a very large Asian population. There are two Japanese cinemas

13:43.060 --> 13:55.620
and two Chinese cinemas and two more Chinese cinemas opening soon just to have a
great access to Asian films more so than most people do around the United

13:55.620 --> 14:07.380
States. I go with them every weekend essentially always watching especially
Japanese films. I've lived in San Francisco five years and of course they have a

14:07.380 --> 14:18.540
large Chinese community and I enjoyed going down there and involving myself in
that culture as much as I could. listen about Tomoe you may not want to answer

14:18.540 --> 14:28.020
this because it might get into your third volume but to me she was at least
she's a searcher she's always even though she achieves almost everything she

14:28.020 --> 14:37.360
sets out to achieve she's dissatisfied she keeps looking she's sort of a
maverick and even marriage and so forth wasn't satisfying to her why is she that

14:37.360 --> 14:49.620
way? are you leading her up towards something? Well, I don't know if she's
exactly a searcher, not someone on any sort of quest. She's someone that

14:49.620 --> 14:58.880
changes, though, in the course of the three books, the third and fourth, which
isn't finished yet. In the first book, I try to present her as somewhat naive.

14:59.460 --> 15:12.020
She's very young, and she does essentially what social society expects of her.
until the very end when she feels somewhat sad that she's actually succeeded.

15:12.180 --> 15:23.660
She's succeeded in doing everything that culture expects. It hasn't made her
particularly happy. So in the second book, she's questioning everything that, in

15:23.660 --> 15:33.300
the first book, she took for granted. And yet still goes along with it. She
continues to do everything that society expects of her. She's obedient to her

15:33.300 --> 15:45.040
lord, who is her husband, and does everything she can to help him as she's
supposed to. And everything comes to no good end at all. And so in the third

15:45.040 --> 15:56.420
book, she is definitely outside the society that she was a part of previously.
She's not actively in rebellion against it, but no longer participating in it.

15:56.420 --> 16:09.660
She becomes essentially a wandering nun. And history allows me to continue to
have her be a swordswoman because there were martial nuns that wandered about

16:09.660 --> 16:19.260
Japan. So she can still be an adventurer and a fighter. She's no longer fighting
for the system that, in the first book, everything was aimed at supporting the

16:19.260 --> 16:32.100
system. And in the third book, everything is outside that system. she never
becomes a total rebel though she never actively seeks to destroy the system ok

16:32.920 --> 16:43.540
I'm an English teacher and I can't help seeing symbolism in the first book she
starts off with as a swords woman, as a warrior she starts off with the double

16:43.540 --> 16:50.780
swords, the equal swords and then changes to the single one did you mean
something that she was a divided person, she was incomplete when she had the

16:50.780 --> 17:03.540
double swords and she had to go to a unified method? Well some of that is maybe
subconscious to me only. I'm not sure. I was thinking of, when I did that, I was

17:03.540 --> 17:17.420
thinking in terms of some martial philosophy that that is perhaps mine as a
martial artist personally. And I was hard to put a handle on that. I think these

17:17.420 --> 17:27.580
books are full of symbolism. Some of it conscious and some of it not. I'm not
quite sure that that was a really important element in that symbolism. I'm not

17:27.580 --> 17:43.460
sure. Okay. In the second volume, I wondered why you were so cruel to Azo Hono O
when you had Tomoe just cut off her arm. I thought it would have been a lot more

17:43.460 --> 17:54.960
satisfactory, at least, to maybe just end her life. Why cut off an arm of a
warrior like that and let her live? I had hoped it was implied that even with

17:54.960 --> 18:06.380
one arm, Azo Hanoro might become a very successful woman warrior herself.
Obviously Azo didn't believe that that would happen to her and she felt it was

18:06.380 --> 18:16.520
cruel to be left alive but it was my intention to imply that she was wrong about
that, that she could still become a successful person although she'd lost that

18:16.520 --> 18:29.120
duel and lost one arm and that story is actually followed up. There's an
anthology edited by Susan Schwartz called Hecate's Cauldron. And I have a short

18:29.120 --> 18:38.640
story in there called The Harmonious Battle, and it tells what happened to
Azulhanovo after she lost her arm. And she becomes an extremely, extremely

18:38.640 --> 18:46.900
successful in a way, kind of ironic way. So it's not a tragedy that she
survived.

18:48.800 --> 18:59.300
Okay, good. Did you say you were writing on the third volume now, and if so,
when would it be out? Very difficult to say when it will be out, since I haven't

18:59.300 --> 19:09.360
finished it. The publisher can't really schedule it for publication until I can
give the publisher an idea when I'll be finished with it. It's taking me a lot

19:09.360 --> 19:22.160
longer than I expected to write this one. but the second one I wrote with
relatively no problem. This one, for whatever reason, is just taking me a lot

19:22.160 --> 19:34.000
longer to do. Okay. Why does the subject of, this is probably an awfully general
question, but why does the subject of women as warriors appeal to you so much?

19:36.340 --> 19:49.300
Maybe partly because I study the martial arts myself personally, and maybe
partly because I've in the past been heavily involved with feminism not so much

19:49.300 --> 19:59.080
involved with it now because I'm too involved with my own writing but I think
from my first three novels the two novels about Tomoe and a third novel called

19:59.080 --> 20:08.880
Swordwoman published by Tor everybody's got the impression that I only write
about sword women when in fact I've just struck on some commercial success with

20:08.880 --> 20:22.540
my material about swordswoman. My short stories cover a much wider range of
material. And I think my novels in the future will also. But I suppose I've just

20:22.540 --> 20:36.360
been very, very much interested in heroic fantasy and not so much interested in
writing about men as about women, right now. Although I hope I'm very fair in my

20:36.360 --> 20:45.760
characterizations of men and have some interesting male characters in all my
work. Oh, yeah, I would agree with that. As long as you mention swordswoman, let

20:45.760 --> 20:54.720
me quickly get on to that for a minute. In a sense, I guess that's the alternate
worlds again. Only in this case you have one heroic world and then one

20:54.720 --> 21:06.800
civilized, meaning the earth. Do you have any particular preference when you set
up an extreme dichotomy like that? I'm not quite sure I understand. Well, do you

21:06.800 --> 21:17.100
do you prefer the heroic world that aaron goes to or the civilized one that she
ends up on earth difficult to say i personally would not have wanted to live in

21:17.100 --> 21:28.360
the world where where aaron went but for her personally it's obviously the world
where she where she should have been allowed to stay i'm almost i'm almost

21:28.360 --> 21:38.760
required to write another book about her that that puts her back there too,
permanently. I think it's clear from the context of the story that N's world is

21:38.760 --> 21:48.740
the place where she belongs. That's not a place where I belong. I wouldn't get
along there at all. I thought it was rather an ugly world. I think our world is

21:48.740 --> 22:00.340
perhaps just as ugly, and perhaps N's world is really just in many ways symbolic
of our own world. That's why it's ugly, and that's why this one's ugly. I

22:00.340 --> 22:08.060
wouldn't have made a choice. I couldn't make a choice between the two worlds. I
don't think if End's world really existed, I would probably decide to stay in

22:08.060 --> 22:18.660
our own. I'm more familiar with it. They're both cruel worlds. Okay, was there a
particular impetus behind that book, or did you just come upon an idea that

22:18.660 --> 22:22.600
seemed interesting to you? Oh, there are many impetuses behind that book.

22:25.700 --> 22:41.020
It's a type of book that essentially, gosh, the basic premise can be found in
some of Edgar Rice Burroughs, Swordsman of Mars type novels, where some man of

22:41.020 --> 22:49.040
Earth is transposed to this world of adventure and gets along fine and dandy,
saves princesses with green eyes and things like that. I just thought it was all

22:49.040 --> 22:57.180
such a lot of nonsense and really childish, And I tried to write what would
really happen to someone if that particular fantasy came true for them, if they

22:57.180 --> 23:06.340
liked this kind of literature, wished that thing would happen to them. And it
does. It happens to them. They go there. Essentially, it's just not instant

23:06.340 --> 23:15.640
success at all. She ends up living like a troll under a bridge, a bum unable to
feed herself or take care of herself. She just can't cope with this change at

23:15.640 --> 23:29.020
all. and very slow how she ends up adapting to that world and learning to love
that world. That was probably my main... The main thing I wanted to do was to

23:29.020 --> 23:41.480
show the absurdity of the fantasy as it usually goes and how it might go instead
if it was done more logically. Okay, I did enjoy that novel very much. There are

23:41.480 --> 23:47.040
a lot of things I could ask about it, but I want to make sure we have time to
cover some more things, so I want to move on for just a few minutes to Amazon's,

23:47.040 --> 23:57.840
the Amazon's books. The first one, Amazon's, what was the story behind your
working on that and how you became interested in doing that volume and how it

23:57.840 --> 24:11.720
was set up? First, that, of course, was my first professional work when I ceased
to be an amateur press person. I'd actually started that project as an amateur

24:11.720 --> 24:22.380
press project. I was going to do an anthology and publish it myself of stories
about women warriors. And so I wrote around to some people, some famous people,

24:22.480 --> 24:30.080
some not so famous people, and asked them if they'd write stories. And they
wrote me great stories. They were just excited by the idea. And up to this

24:30.080 --> 24:41.260
point, heroic fantasy stories, this is like 1978 when I first started doing the
project. There were very, very few heroic fantasy stories with women as

24:41.260 --> 24:51.820
protagonists. Everybody thought it was just great and wonderful, and I was
shocked by the response. So I contacted a publisher, just on the off chance that

24:51.820 --> 25:01.300
they might think it was a wonderful idea too, and they did. So it turned out to
be a professional anthology rather than a small press anthology. And then it

25:01.300 --> 25:10.160
went on to win the World Fantasy Award, and I guess that's when I started to be
able to make my living as an editor and a writer, that everybody started paying

25:10.160 --> 25:21.020
attention to my work. Yeah, I guess the responsive readers must have been pretty
good to that work, too, right? Well, I kind of cheated. I put my address on the

25:21.020 --> 25:32.220
last page of the book, and that caused me to get hundreds and hundreds of
letters. For a while I was getting 20 letters a day, mostly from women, but also

25:32.220 --> 25:43.500
from a lot of guys who were just really tickled to read all these stories. There
was a wide range of people. There were super right-wing people. There were super

25:43.500 --> 25:53.620
left-wing people, just people that just liked stories. Everybody didn't matter
what their personal politics, their persuasion, they just really liked those

25:53.620 --> 26:05.060
stories. And I suppose that means it's fairly successful, although sometimes I
wonder if being that apolitical is a good thing. There were a few people that

26:05.060 --> 26:12.780
hated it because they could tell I was a feminist And they thought that
destroyed the worth of the anthology for me to have a feminist perspective

26:12.780 --> 26:22.740
personally. But mostly everybody liked it, and I certainly did. I've never
gotten more letters for anything else I've ever done. And, of course, that kind

26:22.740 --> 26:32.240
of response must have led into the Amazons, too, then. Yes, sir. Many of the
letters weren't sent to my address. They were sent to the publisher who

26:32.240 --> 26:41.500
forwarded them to me. So the publisher also got to see how many people were
interested. But really the publisher didn't decide that there could be a second

26:41.500 --> 26:52.640
volume until it won the World Fantasy Award. And then he instantly was
interested in a second volume. Gosh, I guess I didn't realize awards did that

26:52.640 --> 27:03.720
much for a book. I thought if a book is good, it would sell without an award on
it. Well, it's very difficult with anthologies especially, because they never

27:03.720 --> 27:10.520
sell as well as novels. The best-selling anthology doesn't sell nearly as well
as a pretty good-selling novel.

27:13.540 --> 27:21.960
Some publishers, therefore, won't publish anthologies. There are many publishers
that won't publish anthologies, because they know a novel will do better. Others

27:21.960 --> 27:31.680
feel a commitment to the short story and to the anthology, and if they make all
their money back a little bit of profit, they have to be satisfied. They're not

27:31.680 --> 27:42.240
going to have any moonfall profits from anthology. They tend to make their
decisions unrelated reasons not so related to the commercial aspect. The

27:42.240 --> 27:50.560
commercial aspect is their first consideration. If an anthology loses money,
there certainly won't be a second one like it. If it makes little money, then

27:50.560 --> 28:00.680
they have to have some additional reason for doing a second one like it. In this
case, it was an award. Okay, I'd like to move on to one more area to make sure

28:00.680 --> 28:09.120
we have time to cover this. I teach a science fiction fantasy course here at
Odessa College, and it's going to be total fantasy next semester, and we're

28:09.120 --> 28:15.780
going to read a lot of heroic fantasy. I'm going to have the students read quite
a bit of it, and I'm probably going to use your Tomoe Gozen novel, the first

28:15.780 --> 28:23.720
one. I'd kind of like to get some of your ideas just about fantasy in general. I
want to ask you, why do people read heroic fantasy, and why has it been so

28:23.720 --> 28:40.200
popular recently? Well, I don't think you can generalize why people like it. I
